## Pipeline Overview

### Step 1 — Feature Engineering (before any drops)

Six new features are created from raw columns before any source column is removed:

| Feature | Description |
|---|---|
| `offer_acceptance_rate` | Ratio of offers accepted to offers received. -1 if no offer received. Correlation = -0.446 |
| `discount_no_response` | Customer received a fee waiver but never responded to any campaign. Churn rate = 36.7% |
| `clv_per_month` | Customer lifetime value divided by tenure months. Stronger signal than CLV alone |
| `investment_depth` | Sum of fixed deposit, investment product, and demat account flags |
| `age_x_balance_decline` | Age multiplied by balance decline percentage. Correlation = 0.454 |
| `city_tier_x_complaints` | City tier (encoded) multiplied by total complaints |

### Step 2 — Feature Selection

Started with 98 columns. 37 columns dropped for the following reasons:

- Missing values: `app_rating_given`
- Zero variance: `credit_card_flag`, `mobile_banking_active_flag`
- Extreme sparsity: `escalation_count`, `unresolved_complaint_count`, `complaint_resolution_time`
- Data leakage: `account_inactive_days` (max value 209 days implies customer has already churned)
- Reverse causality: `retention_offer_received`, `discount_or_fee_waiver_received` (bank pre-flags at-risk customers, not predictors)
- Multicollinearity: three credit utilization versions reduced to `credit_utilization_3m_avg` only
- No lift over baseline: `debt_to_income_ratio` (lift 0.92x), dead campaign signals
- Weak standalone signal: most demographic and product flag columns

Final feature count: 61 features (55 original + 6 engineered)

### Step 3 — Encoding

| Column | Method | Rationale |
|---|---|---|
| `competitor_bank_offer_awareness` | Ordinal (0-3) | Natural severity order |
| `customer_feedback_sentiment` | Ordinal (0-2) | Natural severity order |
| `card_category` | Ordinal (1-4) | Natural tier order |
| `primary_account_type` | One-Hot | Nominal, no natural order |

Test set columns aligned to training set columns after one-hot encoding.

### Step 4 — Log Transformation

Applied `log(1 + x)` to 19 skewed features including loan amounts, balances, transaction values, login recency fields, and CLV-derived columns. Handles outliers without deletion.

### Step 5 — Standard Scaling

Applied `StandardScaler` to 30 continuous features. Scaler fitted on training data only, then applied to validation and test. The scaler is never refit on test data.

### Step 6 — Train / Validation Split

80/20 stratified split with `random_state=42`.

- Train: 6,480 rows, 16.06% churn
- Validation: 1,621 rows, 16.10% churn
- `scale_pos_weight`: 5.22 (used in both models to handle class imbalance)

